The video player behaves as follows:

Playback is 1 packet per second, in increasing packet number order, starting with packet 1 at time! L

At each second t, the player must play packet t

It can play it from the buffer, or

Directly from the packets arriving at time t (if it is the first usable arrival that second).

Any packet with a number greater than the most recently played packet may be stored in a buffer fo future use.

Any packet that has already been played is discarded.

Duplicate packets do not help and can be ignored.

If multiple packets arrive at the same second:

Only one packet is played that second (if possible).

All remaining arriving packets are either buffered (if usable later) or ignored.

Re-buffering starts at the first time t when packet t is not immediately available (neither already in the buffer nor available to play from the arriving packets at that second).

Return the earliest time re-buffering begins. If playback never needs to re-buffer before the stream ends

return -1

